pageContext.description: A complete copper-alloy awl / tracer of probable late Bronze Age date, 68.2mm in length. around two thirds of the length of the object is of square cross section, tapering to a flat chisel-shaped tip (tracer end). The remaining third has sub-rounded cross section, tapering from a square collar of 4.7mm thickness to a sharp point (awl end).
pageContext.notes: Plain copper alloy awls are hard to date precisely but examples of this form are thought to have been introduced in the Bronze Age (2150-800 BC) with most being Late Bronze Age in date (1150-800 BC).
pageContext.subsequentActionTerm: Finder applying for an export licence
